runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1641:/bin/zsh -lc 'rg -n "support|packet semantics|packet|conjugate|helical|canonical|real-valued|real valued|bookkeeping|representation" /Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001' in /Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1643:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/selector.md:9:These three make the strongest portfolio because they cover the full mission risk surface without collapsing into one obstruction style. Chain 04 is the prerequisite gatekeeper: if the object is unstable or circular, later theorem work is fake. Chain 02 then attacks the inherited exact-NS non-isolability pressure in its most mission-aligned quantitative form, and it still pays off on failure because a vanishing-leakage family would become explicit anti-obstruction evidence. Chain 03 preserves the highest-upside adversarial route by directly trying to beat the obstruction with an exact small packet, so the portfolio does not overfit to one no-circuit narrative.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1644:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/selector.md:23:Required to preserve a genuine negative-kill path. It is the highest-upside chain in the portfolio, and even on failure it returns a ranked failure atlas for small exact packets rather than an empty search narrative.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1645:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:11:- The step asks for support, normalization, time window, and spectator size, but it omits several quantities that exact NS actually cares about: phase information, helical sign pattern, amplitude hierarchy, and whether "support" means single modes, conjugate pairs, or packets. That omission matters because triadic forcing depends on more than a support graph.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1646:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:21:- The chain mixes true symmetries with bookkeeping conventions. `rescaling` is not a harmless cosmetic move unless the full NS scaling, including time and viscosity normalization, is specified. `conjugate completion` is not cosmetic either; for real-valued velocity fields it changes what the packet literally is. `packet regrouping` can change nonlinear bookkeeping in a way that is mathematically substantive, not merely presentational.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1647:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:24:- `helical basis choice` is especially slippery here. If the definition is attached to exact mode interactions, basis dependence may reflect a bad representation choice that should be fixed by canonicalization, not a reason to kill the object entirely.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1648:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:25:- The stable/unstable/conditionally stable table is too coarse. Many workable mathematical objects are only stable after choosing a canonical representation. That is not ideal, but it is not obviously fatal for theorem use.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1649:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:29:## Step 3 - Audit dynamical testability on small exact packets
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1650:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:33:- The mission wants a theorem object or a counterexample, not necessarily an object decidable on the tiniest exact packet. Forcing "small exact packet" testability may kill the right definition simply because the phenomenon is inherently multiscale.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1651:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:34:- Requiring a finite interaction table or finite leakage metric biases the search toward toy notions. A serious exact-NS obstruction may only emerge for a family of packets or a scale-separated construction.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1652:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:46:- Missing are edge cases favorable to the opposite conclusion: carefully engineered helical sign patterns, scale-separated packets, sparse triad geometries, or constructions where leakage is present but dynamically negligible. Without those, the audit is not an attack on the definition space; it is mostly an attack on definitions that do not already agree with the prior mission's intuition.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1653:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:57:- A single surviving definition does not imply there is one canonical mission object. Different downstream routes may legitimately need different notions: one leakage-based for obstruction work, one behavioral for adversarial construction work.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1654:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:59:- The final kill condition only flags one kind of circularity: hard-coding Tao's averaged construction back into exact NS language. But circularity can also enter through tuned thresholds, cherry-picked time windows, or choosing a packet representation that predetermines leakage.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1655:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:67:- The ordering is likely wrong. Definitions and exact packet calculations should co-evolve. Here the chain tries to stabilize the object in abstraction before enough contact with the exact triadic law. That is a recipe for false negatives.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1656:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:70:- The chain overstates the need for representation invariance. For this mission, a theorem object may be perfectly acceptable if it is tied to a canonical Fourier/helical presentation. Full robustness under all regroupings is a luxury standard, not obviously the right one.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1657:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:74:  2. Is the object representation-robust?
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1658:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:81:If this chain is used, it should not be the sole gatekeeper. Its strongest contribution is to punish circular, threshold-gerrymandered definitions. Its weakest feature is that it can mistake "not yet canonically phrased" for "mathematically nonexistent." As written, it is valuable as an adversarial side-audit, but too brittle and too meta to deserve unilateral authority over whether the mission object is real.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1659:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:19:- The chain acts as if one can simply "choose" a leakage functional, but the whole mission already knows that this choice is dangerous. Ratios like off-graph interaction strength divided by on-graph interaction strength are not automatically invariant under packetization, normalization, basis choice, or time-window choice.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1660:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:21:- The proposed closure conventions are not clean alternatives on the same footing. Exact Fourier support closure, helical triad closure, and conjugate completion are different layers of bookkeeping, not one menu of mutually exclusive rules.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1661:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:28:### Step 2 - Build the forced spectator ledger for the smallest candidate packets
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1662:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:30:This step risks confusing the smallest analyzable packet with the most relevant packet.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1663:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:32:- "Smallest candidate packets" is a hidden thesis. A leakage lower bound proved only for minimal packets may say nothing about larger packets with redundancy, compensating geometry, or distributed role assignment.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1664:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:34:- The proposed spectator classes are not obviously disjoint in a way that supports clean lower bounds. Mirror modes, companion triads, and feedback channels can interact with each other, so classwise accounting may double-count or hide cancellations.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1665:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:35:- The chain quietly assumes finite closure is the relevant object. But near-closure might still be meaningful for packets with small tails rather than strict finite support closure.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1666:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:39:- "Finite-packet non-closure" is not automatically a stronger obstruction. It only kills one model class. The mission target is near-closed Tao-like behavior, not necessarily strict finite packet closure.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1667:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:46:- "Same normalization" is not a trivial bookkeeping step. Interaction coefficients, energy flux, and amplitude production are different objects. A bound in one may be irrelevant in another.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1668:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:47:- The plan assumes exact coefficient identities and projection geometry can produce sign-definite inequalities. In helical triad algebra, many terms are sign-indefinite and phase-sensitive. The generic outcome is cancellation structure, not monotone leakage.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1669:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:59:- The step acknowledges near-degenerate and specially aligned configurations, but these are not rare corner cases. In a problem about engineered exact packets, they are exactly the cases an adversary will use.
runtime/logs/codex-patlas-exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit-step-001-explorer-001.log:1670:/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:72:- A positive lower bound that depends strongly on packet size, normalization, or role assignment may not deserve to be called a no-near-closure statement.
